The paper is about word embedding algorithms, which are commonly used in natural language processing (NLP) tasks. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the mathematical framework of these algorithms, which involves low rank models and maximum likelihood estimation, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are also likely sub-categories. The empirical evaluations of the algorithms involve neural networks, indicating that cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper emphasizes the practical applications of word embeddings in NLP systems, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
